Question 2.

What is the distribution of backpack weights that students are carrying? Choose an appropriate graph to show the distribution.


backpack %>% 
 group_by(backpack_weight) %>% 
 summarise(counts = n()) %>% 
ggplot() +
  geom_smooth(aes(x = backpack_weight, y = counts), se = FALSE) +
  labs(
  x = "Backpack Weight (lb)",
   y = "Number of Students",
   title = "Weight carried by students"
 ) +
  scale_x_continuous(
    breaks = seq(2,30, by = 2)) +
  scale_y_continuous(
    breaks = seq(1,12, by = 1))
`summarise()` ungrouping output (override with `.groups` argument)

NA
backpack %>% 
 group_by(backpack_weight) %>% 
 summarise(counts = n()) %>% 
ggplot() +
  geom_col(aes(x = backpack_weight, y = counts), fill = "blue") +
  labs(
  x = "\nBackpack Weight (lb)",
   y = "Number of Students",
   title = "Weight carried by students") +
  scale_x_continuous(
    breaks = seq(2,40, by = 2)) +
 scale_y_continuous(
    breaks = seq(1,12, by = 1))

Question 3.

Are there differences in backpack weight between sex?

ggplot(backpack) +
  geom_histogram(aes(x = backpack_weight, fill = sex), col = "white",   show.legend = FALSE, binwidth = 1) +
  facet_wrap(~ sex) +
    labs(
    x = "Backpack Weight (lb)",
    y = "Gender",
    title = "Backpack Weight by Gender"
    ) +
  scale_x_continuous(
    breaks = seq(0,40, by = 5)) +
 scale_y_continuous(
    breaks = seq(1,10, by = 1))
